http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Naturally occurring abrasives.
Direct application of chalk, limestone or dolomite for soil conditioning
Material used for agricultural or horticultural purposes as a fertiliser, soil conditioner or improver.
Natural Stone used in a block, flag or slate form for construction or decorative purposes, or artifacts, e.g. millstones.
Material directly used in the manufacture of cement or mortar.
Material used as a raw material for the manufacture of ceramics and refractories, i.e. whiteware or pottery. Excludes bricks, tiles, pipes and pottery.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/source.value: ProMine EU FP7 project, BGS Mines and Quarries Database

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Material directly used in the manufacture of a product by an industrial chemical process. Includes borates, barite, fluorite, magnesium (magnesite), sodium sulphate, sodium carbonate (trona), pyrite, sulphur, rock salt, strontium, zeolites.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/source.value: ProMine EU FP7 project, BGS Mines and Quarries Database

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Material used in the construction industry. Includes aggregate, dimension & ornamental stones (granite, gabbro, travertine, etc.), gypsum, anhydrite, cement limestone, limestone for lime, marble, sand and gravel.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/source.value: adapted from Glossary of Geology. 4th Edition, AGI

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Any of several hard, inert materials, such as sand, gravel, slag, or crushed stone, used for mixing with a cementing or bituminous material to form concrete or asphalt or used alone, as in railroad ballast or graded fill. Excludes materials for cement making and plaster making.
Material has potential for use in borehole drilling processes, e.g. as a mud weight or viscosity additive.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/source.value: ProMine EU FP7 project, BGS Mines and Quarries Database

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Raw materials in the energy industry. Includes oil, gas, bituminous sandstone and limestone, oil shale, coal, lignite, peat, thorium, uranium.
Clay or shale with particular properties, used for a civil engineering purpose other than as a fill, e.g. liner for landfill, flood defence

http://purl.org/dc/terms/source.value: ProMine EU FP7 project, BGS Mines and Quarries Database

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Direct application K- or P-bearing rock as a fertiliser; rock used for chemical fertiliser production e.g. phosphate; mineral used to prevent caking of fertilizer granules
Material has potential for energy production through burning
Material used as a part of the process in the manufacture of a metallic product.
Precious or semi precious stones or metals for use in jewellery or decorative work
General use in the glass making industry, including fluxes.
Horticultural uses e.g. sand for top dressing, peat
Material used in the manufacture of a product by an industrial process, or in the treatment of a product
Material directly used in the treatment or enhancement of an industrial product, i.e. paper coatings.
Soil and aggregates used for landscaping
Metal ore directly used to produce metals and minerals used in their processing
Ore concentrate of specified metal
Resource end use is for sale to collectors and for education
resource end use is extraction of non-metal elements for direct use, e.g. flourine, bromine, iodine, boron
Material has potential for energy production through use in nuclear reactor
Material directly used in the manufacture of a plaster or plasterboard.
Materials recycled for either remanufacture of a similar product or for use in a different product or manner

Includes abrasives: garnet, staurolite, corundum; asbestos (antophyllite, chrysotile, crocidolite); attapulgite, sepiolite (clay); bentonite (clay); limestone, calcite (filler); diatomite (kieselguhr); graphite; mica; perlite; quartz (massive / block for ferrosilicon); quartz (for optical and piezoelectrical use); silica sand; talc, pyrophyllite; vermiculite; wollastonite.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Material used as a raw material for the manufacture of structural clay products, i.e. Bricks, pipes and tiles.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: This file contains the CGI End Use Potential vocabulary, as defined by the IUGS Commission for Geoscience Information (CGI) Geoscience Terminology Working Group. The vocabulary defines concepts to specify the end-use potential of the Earth Resource (eg for energy, fertilizer, building raw material etc). In the ERML model, a MineralOccurrence is a kind of EarthResource that has an occurrence type category and one or more associated enduse potential concepts. This vocabulary provides the range of values for the end-use potential property of MineralOccurrence. By extension, this vocabulary includes all concepts in this conceptScheme, as well as concepts in any previous versions of the scheme.
